    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>A widow! what a world of sorrow<lb/> and care is comprised in that epithet,<lb/> if
                young, he of whom she is bereaved<lb/> was yet the object of those warm and<lb/>
                gushing affections whose light was the<lb/> bright dream of her maidenhood, and<lb/>
                if of maturer age, years of companionship<lb/> had <add>?</add> those ardent
                feelings only to<lb/> purify <del>them</del> them; the hours of calm<lb/> converse,
                the plans <del>the</del> hopes, wishes of<lb/><sic>of</sic> which their children
                were the theme,<lb/> all have served to deepen the love<lb/> that in the early
                season of their wedded<lb/> life seemed incapable of greater intensity;<lb/> and now
                at none she weeps alone, in<lb/> the first anguish of bereavement what can<lb/>
                console her. Has she ceased to love her<lb/> children, no no but in looking on
                them<lb/> she only thinks alas he is no longer here<lb/> to watch with me their
                growing loveli-<lb/>ness, to check their wayward deed or<lb/> train to better
                thought. But now there<lb/> comes a holy calm, whence is it? see</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>the Book of Books it lies before her “A<lb/> Husband to the Widow, A Father to
                the<lb/> Fatherless.” This gracious promise, the<lb/> sacred injunction defraud not
                nor<lb/> oppress them; yes thus she finds her<lb/> bitter grief allayed, the
                children whom<lb/> God himself makes object of especial<lb/> love, shall she not
                strive to lead them<lb/> to Him, shall she not seek with earnest<lb/> prayer and
                trusting hope His guidance<lb/> in that holiest task a mothers training<lb/> of her
                offspring, and in grateful reliance<lb/> say He who has stricken can console.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">To the <addressee>Rev I Leeser</addressee></p>
            <p>That in our small community, three<lb/> bereavements of the kind alluded to has<lb/>
                occurred in that many weeks, led to to the<lb/> train of thought that if you
                    <add>?</add> please dear<lb/> sir you will give place to in the Occident<lb/> I
                am aware that its adaptation is its only<lb/> merit therefore shall not doubt
                your<lb/> judgment a kindness if you decline it<lb/> Hoping soon to see you in
                health and happiness<lb/> and with regard your friend <persName role="author">L B
                    Hart</persName></p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>Should you publish, do not affix aught<lb/> but <persName>L</persName> or if you choose<lb/>
                <persName>Marianne</persName></p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <addressee>Rev I. Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p>Editor of the Occident</p>
